Intuition
Intuition

The rotated sorted array can be viewed as two individually sorted parts:

Left part: all elements greater than nums[n-1].
Right part: all elements less than or equal to nums[n-1].

Using this observation, we can first determine which part nums[mid] belongs to by comparing it with the last element of the array. Once the part containing mid is known, we decide the search direction based on the relative position of the target.

If mid lies in the left part, a target greater than nums[mid] must also lie to its right. Otherwise, we determine whether the target belongs to the left or right part by comparing it with nums[0].
If mid lies in the right part, a target smaller than nums[mid] must lie to its left. Otherwise, we determine the target's part by comparing it with nums[n-1].

At every iteration, half of the search space is discarded, preserving the logarithmic complexity of binary search.

Time Complexity

Time: O(log n)

Each iteration eliminates half of the remaining search space, just like standard binary search.

Space Complexity

Space: O(1)

Only a few variables are used regardless of the input size.

Code
class Solution:
    def search(self, nums: List[int], target: int) -> int:
        low = 0 
        high = len(nums) - 1
        n = len(nums)
        while low <= high:
            mid = (low+high)//2
            if nums[mid] == target:
                return mid
            # mid is in left part
            if nums[mid] > nums[n-1]:
                if nums[mid] < target:
                    low = mid + 1
                else:
                    if nums[0] <= target:
                        high = mid - 1
                    else:
                        low = mid + 1
            #mid is in right part
            else:
                if nums[mid] > target:
                    high = mid - 1
                else:
                    if target <= nums[n-1]:
                        low = mid + 1
                    else:
                        high = mid - 1
        return - 1
